<Base title="Governance — ostk" description="How ostk governs itself: GPG web of trust, capability pins, and the documents that define the OS.">
  <div class="container">
    <h1>Governance</h1>

    <p class="lede">ostk is governed by signed documents, not by permissions dashboards. Trust is cryptographic. Enforcement is invisible.</p>

    <h2>The trust model</h2>
    <p>Identity in ostk is determined by the <strong>GPG web of trust</strong>. Your trust tier is resolved at boot by checking whether your GPG key carries a cross-signature from a trusted key.</p>
    <p>There are no admin panels. No role assignments. No OAuth scopes. You have a GPG key. The key either carries a cross-signature from a T0 holder, or it doesn't. That's the entire model.</p>

    <h3>How cross-signing works</h3>
    <ol>
      <li>You generate a GPG key and add it to your GitHub account.</li>
      <li>You share your fingerprint with a T0 holder (a project maintainer).</li>
      <li>They sign your key: <code>gpg --sign-key YOUR_FINGERPRINT</code></li>
      <li>They export the signed key: <code>gpg --export --armor YOUR_FINGERPRINT > signed.asc</code></li>
      <li>You import their signature: <code>gpg --import signed.asc</code></li>
      <li>You boot ostk. The kernel detects the cross-signature. You're T1.</li>
    </ol>
    <p>No server was involved. No API was called. The trust relationship exists in the GPG keyring on your machine.</p>

    <h2>The governance documents</h2>
    <p>Four documents define the OS. Each has a specific role:</p>

    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Document</th><th>What it governs</th><th>Who can modify it</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><a href="/docs/humanfile"><strong>HUMANFILE</strong></a></td>
          <td>Models, secrets, trust policy, pin defaults</td>
          <td>T0 only (human + kernel dual-sign)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><a href="/docs/entityfile"><strong>ENTITYFILE</strong></a></td>
          <td>OS identity, key registry, lineage, laws</td>
          <td>T0 only (updated each release by shipping agent)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>AUTHORIZATION.md</strong></td>
          <td>Trust tier definitions, pin policy, escalation path</td>
          <td>T0 only</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>GENESIS.md</strong></td>
          <td>Birth attestation — immutable creation record</td>
          <td>Nobody (append-only, signed at creation)</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <p>These files are protected by the <code>modify-governance</code> deny token. Any agent at T1 or below is silently blocked from writing to them. The agent never knows the write was denied. The audit trail records it.</p>

    <h2>Capability pins</h2>
    <p>Pins are invisible capability boundaries. They define what agents <em>cannot</em> do — not what they can. The design inverts the traditional permission model.</p>

    <h3>Traditional model</h3>
    <pre><code># "Grant access to X" — the agent must request it
agent.request_permission("write", "src/")
if approved: proceed()</code></pre>

    <h3>ostk model</h3>
    <pre><code># The agent writes normally. The OS decides.
# If denied, the write silently fails. The agent never knows.
echo "new code" > src/main.rs   # ← blocked for T2, allowed for T1</code></pre>

    <p>Three deny tokens control the boundaries:</p>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Token</th><th>What it denies</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><code>write-kernel</code></td><td>Writes to <code>.ostk/</code> — the OS state directory</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>modify-governance</code></td><td>Writes to HUMANFILE, ENTITYFILE, GENESIS.md, AUTHORIZATION.md, Agentfile</td></tr>
        <tr><td><code>write-src</code></td><td>Writes to source code</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h3>Floor semantics</h3>
    <p>Your trust tier sets a <strong>floor</strong> — the minimum set of restrictions. Explicit pins can add more restrictions but never remove tier defaults.</p>
    <p>A T2 user who sets <code>OSTK_PIN=my-permissive-pin</code> still cannot write source. The kernel computes the union: <code>tier_denies ∪ explicit_denies</code>. The floor holds.</p>

    <h2>The five laws</h2>
    <p>These are not guidelines. They are load-bearing constraints. Every design decision in the OS must satisfy all five.</p>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>The write path is invisible.</strong> Agents edit files normally. Coordination happens underneath. No new tools to learn.</li>
      <li><strong>Agents are ephemeral.</strong> They crash, compact, lose context. State lives in the filesystem, not in the agent.</li>
      <li><strong>Coordinate through the filesystem.</strong> No messaging buses. No inboxes. Agents write files. The kernel resolves conflicts.</li>
      <li><strong>Optimistic concurrency.</strong> No locks. Agents write freely. Conflicts resolved, not prevented.</li>
      <li><strong>Invisible infrastructure.</strong> If you have to think about the OS, the OS failed.</li>
    </ol>

    <h2>Needles</h2>
    <p>Work items in ostk are called <strong>needles</strong> — as in needle-in-a-haystack. Each needle is an executable unit of work with a title, priority, and test criteria. The kernel tracks them, agents execute them, the audit trail records completion.</p>
    <p>Needles are filed with <code>ostk needle add</code>, compiled from unstructured thinking with <code>ostk compile</code>, and closed when the work is done. The backlog is visible at <code>ostk show needles</code>.</p>
    <p>That's the whole metaphor. Needles are work items. The haystack is the project state. The OS helps you find and resolve them.</p>

    <h2>The signing chain</h2>
    <p>Every release follows the same chain:</p>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Development</strong> — commits signed by the developer's personal key</li>
      <li><strong>Release</strong> — the <code>ostk.ai</code> repository commit signed by the institutional key (<code>contact@ostk.ai</code>)</li>
      <li><strong>Binary</strong> — release binaries signed by the CI key (cross-signed by root)</li>
      <li><strong>Verification</strong> — any user can verify any artifact against the public key (<code>prime.asc</code> in the repo)</li>
    </ol>
    <p>The root key certifies the CI key. The CI key signs binaries. Users verify against the root. One chain, fully offline-verifiable.</p>

    <h2>Source availability</h2>
    <p>The kernel binary is distributed as GPG-signed release artifacts. The <a href="https://github.com/os-tack/ostk.ai">os-tack/ostk.ai</a> repository — containing the governance documents, signing keys, install script, and release configuration — is open source under MIT license.</p>
    <p>The kernel source is not currently published. The governance model, trust chain, and all verification artifacts are fully public and auditable.</p>
  </div>
</Base>

